# African Federation Treaty Framework (AFTF)

**Operational Architecture for Continental Economic Sovereignty**

[![DOI](https://zenodo.org/badge/DOI/10.5281/zenodo.17670880.svg)](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.17670880)
[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-All%20Rights%20Reserved-red.svg)](./LICENSE.md)

---

## About

The African Federation Treaty Framework provides operational machinery for continental coordination across:

- **Financial Architecture**: Sovereign development finance, mineral funds, monetary integration
- **Security Integration**: United African Defence Force, cyber defence, space surveillance  
- **Resource Sovereignty**: Critical mineral governance, agricultural independence, energy transition
- **Digital Sovereignty**: Data localisation, African digital infrastructure, technology development
- **Trade Architecture**: Customs union, services integration, investment frameworks

**Published:** 21 November 2025  
**Author:** David Okiki Amayo Jr., The Ndege Group  
**DOI:** [10.5281/zenodo.17670880](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.17670880)

---

## Framework Components

### Part I: Institutional Architecture
The tripartite system comprising:
- African Sovereign Development Finance Corporation (ASDFC)
- United African Defence Force Central Command (UADFCC)
- Continental Governance Authority (CGA)

### Part II: Financial Architecture
- African Sovereign Development Finance Fund (capitalisation: EUR 410 billion Phase 1)
- African Rare Earth Mineral Fund
- OmniGaza¬Æ blockchain platform specifications
- Phased monetary coordination pathway (2026-2040)

### Part III: Security Architecture
- Standing force: 25,000 personnel across 5 Rapid Response Brigades
- Reserve component: 100,000 personnel
- Cyber Defence Centre (Kigali, Rwanda)
- Space Surveillance Network (Egypt, Kenya, South Africa)
- Budget: 0.5% of combined GDP

### Part IV: Resource Sovereignty
- Critical mineral governance (4-tier classification system)
- Mandatory beneficiation requirements
- Export licensing tied to local processing
- Joint venture minimums (51% African ownership)

### Part V: Digital Sovereignty
- 100% local storage for government data
- Sovereign cloud requirements for health records
- 48-hour local retention for telecommunications metadata
- African Internet Exchange (Cairo)
- Quantum communication network

### Part VI: Trade Architecture
- Single customs territory with Common External Tariff (CET)
- Automated customs clearance
- Harmonised product standards
- Professional mobility framework
- Banking licence passporting

### Part VII: Implementation Machinery
- Entry requirements: 15 nations signed, 8 ratified, EUR 500B combined GDP
- Phased integration: Observer ‚Üí Associate ‚Üí Full Member ‚Üí Strategic Partner
- Performance metrics across economic, security, and governance indicators

### Part VIII-X: Dispute Resolution, Sanctions, Final Provisions
- Four-tier dispute resolution hierarchy
- Graduated sanction system (Warning ‚Üí Restriction ‚Üí Suspension ‚Üí Expulsion)
- Amendment procedures requiring 5 member state co-sponsors

